Super Eagles winger Moses Simon has dedicated his Confederation of African Football (CAF) Player of the Year nomination to his coaches, teammates, family and friends. CAF announced yesterday the 30 nominees for the 2022 African Player of the Year, with Nantes winger as the only Nigerian in the race for the prestigious individual award. The 26-year-old enjoyed a great season with Nantes in the French Ligue 1, registering six goals and eight assists in 30 appearances to help the club to a respectable ninth-place finish and the Coupe de France title.   Olympic champion pulls out of Stockholm 100m     Oshoala launches football academy     DStv, GOtv to beam 2022 WAFCON in Morocco   Simon needs to see off competition from some of the biggest names in African football like Bayern Munich’s new star Sadio Mane, Liverpool duo Naby Keita and Mohamed Salah, Ajax’s Ivorian hitman Sebastien Haller, Manchester City winger Riyad Mahrez and Chelsea goalkeeper Edouard Mendy. In a tweet reacting to the news yesterday, Moses wrote: “Woke up to the news of my nomination for CAF Player Of The Year Award (MEN). This is not for me but for my coaches, teammates, family and friends. To God be the glory.” Meanwhile, in the CAF Young Player of the Year category, Akinkunmi Amoo will battle the likes of Burkina Faso’s Dango Ouattara, Ilaix Moriba of Guinea and Hannibal Mejbri of Tunisia for the award after being named as one of the ten nominees. The 20-year-old attacking midfielder Amoo enjoyed a stunning 2021 season at Hammarby, making 36 appearances in domestic competitions in which he was involved in 18 goals (13 goals, 5 assists), earning a move to Danish powerhouse FC Copenhagen in the January transfer window before winning the Danish top-flight with The Lions four months later.